title: Create Hello World Function
question_content:
Write a function createHelloWorld. It should return a new function that always returns "Hello World".
 
Example 1:

Input: args = []
Output: "Hello World"
Explanation:
const f = createHelloWorld();
f(); // "Hello World"
The function returned by createHelloWorld should always return "Hello World".

Example 2:

Input: args = [{},null,42]
Output: "Hello World"
Explanation:
const f = createHelloWorld();
f({}, null, 42); // "Hello World"
Any arguments could be passed to the function but it should still always return "Hello World".

 
Constraints:

	0 <= args.length <= 10

# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
>The problem requires us to create a function that returns another function that always returns "Hello World". This can be achieved by simply defining a function that returns another function that has the constant value of "Hello World".

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
>We can use a higher order function to create and return a new function that always returns "Hello World". This can be done by defining a function that returns another function that has "Hello World" as its return value.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
>The time complexity of this function is O(1) because it simply returns a constant value.

<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
>The space complexity of this function is O(1) because it does not use any additional memory besides the returned function.

# Code
>There are several ways to implement a function that returns a new function that always returns "Hello World". Here are three possible solutions in JavaScript:

- Using an arrow function with implicit return:

```
const createHelloWorld = () => () => "Hello World";
```
>This creates an arrow function that takes no arguments and returns another arrow function that always returns "Hello World".

- Using a function expression with explicit return:
```
const createHelloWorld = function() {
  return function() {
    return "Hello World";
  }
};
```
>This is a similar approach as the previous one, but using a regular function expression instead of an arrow function.

- Using a function declaration:
```
function createHelloWorld() {
  return function() {
    return "Hello World";
  }
}
```
>This is the most verbose option, but it works in the same way as the previous two.

>All three solutions return a new function that always returns "Hello World", regardless of the arguments passed to it. Here's an example of how to use them:

```
const f = createHelloWorld();
console.log(f()); // "Hello World"
console.log(f("foo", "bar")); // "Hello World"
Both calls to f will return "Hello World", even though different arguments were passed to it.
```

# Intuition
The intention behind the code is straightforward – we want to provide a factory function that, when invoked, returns another function. This returned function, when called, will always return the string "Hello World" regardless of the arguments provided to it.

# Approach
1. We define a function createHelloWorld that does not take any parameters.
2. The function, when called, returns an inner function (another example of a JavaScript closure).
3. This inner function is designed to accept any number of arguments (denoted by the spread syntax ...args). However, it doesn't use these arguments in any way.
4. Regardless of the arguments passed to this inner function, it always returns the string "Hello World".

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(1): The inner function only returns a constant string, "Hello World", which is a constant-time operation.

- Space complexity:
O(1): The inner function doesn't utilize any data structures or additional space based on the input size. It simply returns a constant string, which requires constant space.

# Code
The provided code gives a clear example of how one can create and then utilize the createHelloWorld function:

```
/**
 * @return {Function}
 */
var createHelloWorld = function() {
    
    return function(...args) {
       return "Hello World"
    }
};
```
While the f function can accept arguments, they have no effect on its behavior or output. For example:
```
/**
 * const f = createHelloWorld();
